member.remarks:

Code example:

List<string> domainNames = new List<string>{ "SA", "CORE0", "RING0" };
string plist = "PlistName";
string conditionName = "ALL_DOMAINS";
List<string> railConfigurationNames = new List<string>{"ConfigSetPointOne", "TimingPin"};
var domainObjectWithConditionAndRailSupport = Prime.Base.ServiceStore<IVoltageService>.CreateFivrDomainsAndConditionWithRails(domainNames, conditionName, plist, railConfigurationNames, someSessionContext);


DVLR rail configurations are not supported due to not providing the necessary pin attributes. Method is meant to be used when DLVR are not needed.


            Code example:

            List<string> domainNames = new List<string>{ "DPS1", "DPS2", "DPS3" };
            var plist = "PLIST";
            List<string> railConfigurationNames = new List<string>{"PinOne", "ConfigSetPointOne", "PinTwo"};
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> dlvrPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"PinOne", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"PinTwo", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> domainPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"DomainPin1", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"DomainPin2", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            this.dpsDomainObjectWithRailSupport = Prime.Base.ServiceStore<IVoltageService>.CreateVForcePinAttributeWithRails(domainNames, plist, domainPinAttributes, railConfigurationNames, dlvrPinAttributes, someSessionContext);


            This is meant to be used with DPS domains only. DPS domains are defined in the domain input file to the service. They work similar to a DPS pin but also support DPS domain groups.

Plist allows the rail conditional pattern modify to be only done on the provided plist.


            Code example:

            List<string> domainNames = new List<string>{ "DPS1", "DPS2", "DPS3" };
            var plist = "PLIST";
            List<string> railConfigurationNames = new List<string>{"ConfigSetPointOne", "Timing0"};
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> domainPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"DomainPin1", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"DomainPin2", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            this.dpsDomainObjectWithRailSupport = Prime.Base.ServiceStore<IVoltageService>.CreateVForcePinAttributeWithRails(domainNames, plist, domainPinAttributes, railConfigurationNames, someSessionContext);


            This is meant to be used with DPS domains only. DPS domains are defined in the domain input file to the service. They work similar to a DPS pin but also support DPS domain groups.

Plist allows the rail conditional pattern modify to be only done on the provided plist.

Does not support DLVR since no pin attributes are provided for DLVR.


            Code example:

            List<string> domainNames = new List<string>{ "DPS1", "DPS2", "DPS3" };
            List<string> railConfigurationNames = new List<string>{"PinOne", "ConfigSetPointOne", "PinTwo"};
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> dlvrPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"PinOne", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"PinTwo", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> domainPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"DomainPin1", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"DomainPin2", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            this.dpsDomainObjectWithRailSupport = Prime.Base.ServiceStore<IVoltageService>.CreateVForcePinAttributeWithRails(domainNames, domainPinAttributes, railConfigurationNames, dlvrPinAttributes, someSessionContext);


            This is meant to be used with DPS domains only. DPS domains are defined in the domain input file to the service. They work similar to a DPS pin but also support DPS domain groups.

No plist is provided so if conditional pattern modifies are used they will affect all patterns they are configured to modify. Refer to  for more details.


            Code example:

            List<string> domainNames = new List<string>{ "DPS1", "DPS2", "DPS3" };
            List<string> railConfigurationNames = new List<string>{"ConfigSetPointOne", "Timing0"};
            Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>> domainPinAttributes = new Dictionary<string, Dictionary<string, string>>{
                {"DomainPin1", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            {"DomainPin2", { "AtributeNameOne", "AtributeValueOne" }, { "AtributeNameTwo", "AtributeValueTwo" }},
            };
            var dpsDomainObjectWithRailSupport = Prime.Base.ServiceStore<IVoltageService>.CreateVForcePinAttributeWithRails(domainNames, domainPinAttributes, railConfigurationNames, someSessionContext);


            This is meant to be used with DPS domains only. DPS domains are defined in the domain input file to the service. They work similar to a DPS pin but also support DPS domain groups.

Plist allows the rail conditional pattern modify to be only done on the provided plist.

Does not support DLVR since no pin attributes are provided for DLVR.

No plist is provided so if conditional pattern modifies are used they will affect all patterns they are configured to modify. Refer to  for more details.


